    "**(core)** In this section we investigate how to produce and plot Julia sets, and display a sequence of images of these sets as an animated film. These Julia sets have parameter $j_p = 0.7885e^{{\\alpha}i}$, for small non-negative $\\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R}$. We generate 200 image files - one for each Julia set as $\\alpha$ takes 200 different values. These are then played in a sequence, using a `pygame` animation, to produce a film of the varying sets. \n",
    "\n",
    "**(Explanation)** In this section we create code that generates animated Julia set fractals as required in the question.\n",
     "In general, the three main parts are: `julia_escape_smooth`, which creates a smooth Julia fractal image; `generate_julia_frames`, which creates a sequence of Julia set images; and `play_frames_pygame`, which plays the saved images.\n",
     "The `julia_escape_smooth` function creates a grid of complex numbers (`Z`) and iterates the function tracking how quickly each point escpaes beyond the radius **R**, using a smooth gradient. The points that dont escape beofre `max_iter` are assigned the maximum value.  The function returns a 2D array of escape-time values that can be plotted as a fractal image. \n",
     "The function `generate_julia_frames` creates an output folder, generates `n_frames` evenly spaced angles from $0$ to $2 \pi$. For each angle, it computes $c = r e ^ (ia)$ and calls `julia_escape_smooth` to create a fractal image. It then saves each frame as `julia_000.png`, `julia_001.png` etc and returns the folder holding the images. This can be turned into an animation. \n",
     "The `play_frames_pygame` function uses Pygame to load all the images in the folder and playback the frames like a video in a loop. It also allows for interactive control. \n",
    "[unfinished]"
   ]
